## SYSTEM OVERVIEW

**KarlOps L** is a streamlined, chat-first operational system built on the learnings of KarlOps v1.
Named after Karl the bad llama (Llamas with Hats). Logo: target reticle KO icon (SVG at public/ko-icon.svg).

**Tagline:** "Chaos, polished."
**Working name:** KarlopsL ("L for Light, which it really isn't")

**Design philosophy:**
- Chat is the primary interface
- Modal-first for find/work interactions — split panel (list left, edit right) for FC objects
- Bucket view for priority pulse
- LLM is an active participant — intake, restructure, inference
- No hierarchy navigation — search and chat replace it
- Implementation type drives vocabulary AND is the future licensing/feature gate
- Tags do the organizational work hierarchy used to do
- Field metadata drives ALL display, validation, and form rendering — no exceptions
- User situation brief is Karl's brain — he reads it before every response

**Core loop:** Capture → Prioritize → Work → Communicate → Document

---

## WHAT KARLOPS L IS NOT

- Not a project manager
- Not a hierarchy navigator
- Not infinitely configurable by the user

It is a **pressure system**. Everything lives in one pool, constantly re-ranked by what's on fire.
Tags tell you what domain it belongs to. Buckets tell you when. Chat helps you restack when the day shifts.

---

## PRODUCT FAMILY — IMPLEMENTATION TYPE AS PRODUCT LINE

KarlOps L is the engine. The `implementation_type` field is a product line selector, not just a feature flag.
Each product is a skin on the same engine — same DB, same Karl, same FC objects — different vocabulary,
seeded templates, and UI focus.

**Confirmed product lines:**
- `personal` — default, full KarlOps L experience
- `pip` — PIP Buster: evidence logging, requirement mapping, formal response generation
- `grade` — Grade Booster: assignment tracking, evidence of work, professor-facing reports (future)
- `enterprise` — multi-user, shared data (future)

**Key insight from first demo (Apr 12):**
PIP Buster needs a radically simplified UI skin. Users under PIP stress cannot learn a system.
The PIP Buster UI should show ONE thing: "What did you do today? Tell me."
Karl captures, files, maps to requirements in the background.
Report generation is a separate flow — possibly manager/advocate facing.
The full KarlOps L UI is too complex for high-stress single-purpose use.

**Architecture implication:**
Same DB, same Karl, same FC objects underneath.
PIP Buster = stripped UI wrapper over KarlOps L engine.
This is a strong commercial angle — purpose-built interfaces for high-stakes moments.

**Product/business notes (Apr 24):**
- Productization is an open question — Mike may prefer keeping this as a personal ops system
- Partner model (like ghostwriter) is an option if commercialization happens
- Internal Airtable dashboard integration is a near-term goal (push extract output to Airtable)

---

## USE CASE: PIP BUSTER

KarlOps L was originally built under PIP pressure and is proven for that use case.
The `pip` implementation type configures vocabulary for PIP response tracking.

**PIP workflow:**
- Capture — log what you did, fast, as it happened
- Chat as analyst — Karl reads activity against requirements
- Karl surfaces patterns — what's covered, what's thin, what needs more evidence
- Document generation — pull into a formal PIP response template via Extracts

**Key vocabulary differences (pip vs personal):**
- completion → Evidence
- context → Requirement Area
- Everything else identical

---

## ARCHITECTURE DECISIONS

### Hierarchy
- **REMOVED:** Global layer, Focus Area layer
- **Context** — lightweight FK on task (NOT a scope parent). Four seeded: The Unobsolete, Job Hunt, Personal, Work
- **TOP LEVEL:** Task — context is just a label/grouping
- Tags provide domain grouping, not structural hierarchy

### Task Promotion (Curation Gate)
- Tasks land in `capture` bucket by default
- A task is **curated** when it has: a non-capture bucket + at least one tag
- Task pills: single line — identifier, title (truncated), status (if not Open), target date. Tags REMOVED from pills.
- Capture tasks display: identifier + title only
- Cannot move a task TO capture via the detail modal (must move OUT)
- Delegate bucket — requires delegated_to (uuid FK to People tag). Use DelegateModal.

### Task Identifiers — ALL FC OBJECTS HAVE IDENTIFIERS
Hardcoded in UI — stable, never changes per implementation type.
```
N   = now
S   = soon
RW  = realwork
L   = later
D   = delegate
CP  = capture
CM  = completion
MT  = meeting
EX  = extract (external_reference)
TM  = template (document_template)
CT  = contact
```
Format: `PrefixN` e.g. `N1`, `RW2`, `CM1`, `MT3`, `EX1`, `TM1`, `CT1`
- Identifiers computed at display time from sorted list position — NOT stored in DB
- Karl references tasks by identifier in chat commands
- **CRITICAL:** Identifier positions are context-filter-dependent. When UI is filtered to a context,
  Karl resolves identifiers against the same filtered list. context_filter is passed from workspace
  through the full stack: page.tsx → route.ts → routeCommand() → buildKarlContext() → resolveIdentifier()

### Implementation Type
- Drives vocabulary, starter tags, UI labels, and future feature gating
- Set per user at onboarding
- NOT configurable by the user after setup
- Is the product line selector for the product family

### Concept Registry (SYSTEM TABLE)
- No user_id — filtered by `ko_user.implementation_type`
- RLS: authenticated read, no user writes
- Admin panel Concepts tab is read-only
- Two implementation types seeded: `personal` (19 rows), `pip` (19 rows)
- Unique constraint: `(implementation_type, concept_key)`
- **Also used as `ko_concept_registry` in backend queries** — Karl reads bucket/object icons from here

### User Situation
- `user_situation` table — free text brain dump Karl reads before every response
- One active situation per user (`is_active` unique index)
- Fields: `name`, `brief` (free text), `is_active`, `chat_history_depth`, `completion_window_days`
- Defaults: `chat_history_depth = 15`, `completion_window_days = 7`
- Managed via Admin → My Situation tab

### Karl's Context Bundle — SPLIT ARCHITECTURE (v0.9.1)

Context is split into static and dynamic for prompt caching efficiency.

**Static context (cached — `buildKarlStaticContext`):**
- Field metadata (description + llm_notes per field)
- Concept registry (bucket/object icons and labels)
- Task statuses (label → uuid map)
- Learned vocab and rules
- Available tags (names only)
- Available contexts (name|uuid pairs)

**Dynamic context (never cached — `buildKarlDynamicContext`):**
- Situation brief
- Last N chat messages (trimmed to chat_history_depth)
- Bucket snapshot — titled tasks with identifiers AND tags in brackets, capture as count only
- Recent completions — titles only, windowed by completion_window_days
- Open meetings snapshot
- FC snapshots (completions, extracts, templates, contacts)
- Karl observations

**How it flows through the stack:**
```
route.ts → buildKarlContextSplit(user_id, context_filter)
         → formatStaticContextForPrompt(ctx.static)   → system block with cache_control
         → formatDynamicContextForPrompt(ctx.dynamic)  → prepended to last user message
```

**Context filter:** When UI is filtered to a context, task query is filtered to match.
Karl's snapshot matches exactly what the user sees.

**Deep bundle (analysis calls only — `buildKarlDeepContext`):**
- Everything in base
- Full completions with outcomes in window
- Open tasks grouped by context (includes tags)

**Analysis triggers:**
analyze, analysis, review, summarize, summary, make the case, what have i done,
show me, evidence, how am i doing, this week, this month, against my, pip, requirement, progress

### Session History
- `ko_session.messages` — JSONB array, one row per user
- Format: `[{ role: 'user'|'karl', content: string, ts: string }]`
- Trimmed to `chat_history_depth * 2` on every append
- Cleared on every login (fresh session each day)
- Anthropic requires first message to be `user` role — leading assistant messages stripped

### Field Metadata Model
- `ko_field_metadata` drives ALL field rendering, validation, and form behavior
- `insert_behavior`: `required` | `optional` | `automatic`
- `update_behavior`: `editable` | `readonly` | `automatic`
- `fk_table` + `fk_label`: drives FK dropdown resolution
- `display_order`: < 999 = show, 999 = hide
- **Field metadata is the source of truth — never hardcode field behavior in UI**
- Column name is `field` (not `field_name`)
- Unique constraint: `(user_id, object_type, field)` — added Apr 14
- Two columns: `description` (canonical what-it-is) and `llm_notes` (Karl's working notes)
  Both seeded for all FC object fields. Both included in every Karl call via fieldKnowledge block.

### Defaults System
- `ko_default_registry` stores per-user defaults per object_type/field
- Task defaults: `bucket_key = capture`, `task_status_id = <open>`
- Tag default: `tag_group_id = <General>`

### Tag System — CORE ARCHITECTURE
Tags are the organizational backbone. Everything is tagged. Tags replace hierarchy.

**Tag groups (seeded for Mike):**
- People — one tag auto-created per contact
- Organizations — companies and institutions
- Systems — tools and platforms
- Activities — domains of work and life
- Projects — discrete bounded efforts
- Personal — health, learning, finances
- Places — locations
- General — catch-all
- Roles — Manager, Colleague, Client, Partner, Vendor, Recruiter, Advocate, Personal

**Tag rules:**
- Max 5 tags per object (meetings: 5 for tags, 15 for attendees — separate fields)
- Tags stored as raw name strings NOT UUIDs
- Chat: Karl suggests from existing tags only — never creates tags in chat
- Modal: TagPicker with Karl suggest can create new tags (saves to DB)
- TagManagerModal: standalone tag/group creation with Karl suggest

**Attendees architecture (REVISED in v0.7.0):**
- `meeting.attendees` — RESTORED as `text[]` column. Separate from `tags[]`.
- Rationale: meetings can have 15+ people; mixing attendees into tags[] pollutes the tag signal.
  "Was in the room" ≠ "is involved in this situation". Critical distinction for PIP Buster.
- Attendees picker: People tags only, maxTags=15
- Tags picker: all tags, maxTags=5
- task.delegated_to — uuid FK to People tag. Required when bucket = delegate.
- DelegateModal — standalone component for delegation. Triggered by drag-drop or chat delegation_pending.

### Contact System
- `contact` table — lightweight people directory
- Auto-creates a People tag on contact save (tag name = contact name)
- Role and Organization are tag FKs (filtered pickers — Roles group and Organizations group)
- FC object: `CT` identifier, `#991b1b` wine/maroon accent

**Contact schema:**
```
contact_id              uuid PK
user_id                 uuid FK ko_user
name                    text NOT NULL
email                   text
primary_contact_method  text
contact_method_detail   text
role_tag_id             uuid FK tag (Roles group only)
organization_tag_id     uuid FK tag (Organizations group only)
notes                   text
tag_id                  uuid FK tag (auto-created People tag)
is_archived             boolean DEFAULT false
created_at              timestamptz
updated_at              timestamptz
```

### LLM Role
- **Intake:** Dump new info, LLM classifies intent and structures it
- **Confirmation before write** — Karl always asks before inserting/updating
- **Tag suggestion on capture:** After classifying capture_task/capture_tasks, Karl makes a second
  lightweight call to suggest tags from existing set. Tags included in confirmation message.
- **Long text dumps:** If user pastes a long description (500+ chars or doc signals), treat as
  process_document — identify content type, map to correct FC object fields, return pending.

